<div id="review_1567700010" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1567700010" />
    <a title="Karen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7648379-karen"><img alt="Karen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1501724896p2/7648379.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1567700010?book_show_action=true">Mar 03, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Karen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Karen" href="/user/show/7648379-karen">Karen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/27823091-shattered-lies">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7648379-karen?shelf=netgalley">netgalley</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1567700010" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13263412460065262949">Once I started reading this book, I couldn&apos;t put it down. From the description, I was expecting a typical mystery type of novel...and was I ever wrong! This book is a mystery to some extent, but also so much more! This story was complex, but so well written! The emotions were genuine and heartfelt, to say the least.<br/><br/>The story is about Kate Thayer, a veterinarian that is in charge of running the family horse farm. One day while she is in her grandmother&apos;s attic, she finds a diary written by her mo</span>
  <span id="freeText13263412460065262949" style="display:none">Once I started reading this book, I couldn't put it down. From the description, I was expecting a typical mystery type of novel...and was I ever wrong! This book is a mystery to some extent, but also so much more! This story was complex, but so well written! The emotions were genuine and heartfelt, to say the least.<br /><br />The story is about Kate Thayer, a veterinarian that is in charge of running the family horse farm. One day while she is in her grandmother's attic, she finds a diary written by her mother. Any time someone reads a diary written by a family member, it's a given that things will change, and usually not for the better. There are always secrets in a diary, and in this case, it was secrets Kate never would have guessed in a million years. As the dirty little secrets are revealed, Kate struggles to accept that her life is not anything like she thought it was, especially not the family she thought she knew so well. Betrayal is hard to deal with no matter who causes it, but it is even harder to deal with when that betrayal is done by your own family! There are flashbacks that are written to portray what life was like living in the Deep South, both in the past and the present, and that helps to tell the story. <br /><br />The biggest secret in the diary is one I refuse to give out, mainly because I don't want to spoil the book, but also because that is the main reason this book is so hard to put down. S.J. Francis knows how to write a novel, and definitely knows how to grab your attention from the beginning to the very end. The secrets are revealed one by one, and that leaves plenty of twists and turns throughout the story. The emotions are definitely real, and I truly felt for Kate and all she had to deal with. I couldn't imagine having my life turned upside the way Kate's life was. I not only had sympathy for Kate, but I also had it for her grandmother as well. Their relationship has changed because of the things Kate finds out while reading the diary, and both try to work at rebuilding that relationship as the book goes on. I absolutely loved the writing style of S.J. Francis. I know this is a book that will stay with me for a very long time, and one I know I will read again. I would highly recommend this book!<br /><br />I was given a digital copy of this book from Black Opal Books and NetGalley in exchange for an honest review.<br /><br /><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/26837899.Shattered_Lies" title="Shattered Lies by S.J. Francis" rel="nofollow noopener">Shattered Lies</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="13263412460065262949" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


